Hello...

This is a LoRA for Anzu Mazaki or Tea Gardner character from Yu-Gi-Oh Dark Side of Dimension, trained in Anythingv4.5 for 20 epochs with 23 images * 28 repeats,

its match the character pretty well with model like anything or any anime models, for more information you can see the image previews.

for the weight i recommended using around 0.6-0.8.

as for the trigger words, i think you can use

anzu dsod, 1girl, solo, smile, blue_eyes, pink skirt, (yellow turtleneck:1.8), brown_hair, thighhighs, jewelry, ponytail, sleeveless, belt, necklace, scrunchie,

i guess that is all, thanks you....

Edit:
So i forgot some images that i use for the preview using control net when looking for pose or propotions, Here some guide to use ControlNet

  • Go towards extensions tabs and install this extension, https://github.com/Mikubill/sd-webui-controlnet

  • Download ControlNet model (https://huggingface.co/lllyasviel/ControlNet/tree/main/models) (recomended the openpose one) and place it inside sd-webui-controlnet/models extension folder

  • After installing, a tab named Control Net should be appeared in txt2img or img2img

  • Open the tab and use this image as a guidelines, pretty much use openpose preprocessor and openpose model then place the image that you want to use inside the tab.

  • Sometimes this method not working, you can use openpose stickman instead, here my collection of openpose stickman (set preprocessor to none like this)

  • Then just generate images like usual, just leave the ControlNet enabled. the image should resemble the pose

items.name: yden
items.description:
2023/4/20 更新了 yden-V3

由于V3版本和前两个版本的融合配方完全不同，因此对构图的改变是很大的，但相比前两个版本，V3版本对于手部有良好的表现，尤其是在高steps的条件下。

所有示例图像均使用txt2img功能生成，所使用的VAE为原生VAE。

Due to my poor English proficiency, I used ChatGPT to translate Chinese into English. Please bear with me.

The following is the translated description:

Due to the completely different fusion formula between V3 version and the previous two versions, there are significant changes in composition. However, compared to the previous two versions, V3 version has good performance for hands, especially under high steps conditions.

All example images were generated using txt2img function and native VAE was used.

————————————————————————————————

2023/3/25 更新了 yden-V2

作为yden的新版本，它和V1一样都是为了生成动漫风格的图片而被创造的模型，且同样已被压缩至fp16，它可以在保持原来的效果和速度的同时减少模型大小。

相较于V1版本，V2版本生成的图片画面会更加精细，且构图有比较大的改变。

在参数设置方面和V1版本没有任何区别，另外在此强烈推荐使用Hires.fix功能，以便更好的发挥这个模型的潜力。

————————————————————————————————

以下是yden-V1的介绍

这是一个用来生成动漫风格的模型，我已将该模型压缩成fp16，它可以在保持原来的效果和速度的同时减少模型大小。

示例图像均由novelai原版VAE生成。

以下是推荐参数：

Sampler：DPM++ 2M Karras

steps：22

CFG Scale：7

Negative prompt：(worst quality, low quality:1.4)

Hires.fix：R-ESRGAN 4x+ Anime6B

Hires steps：10

Denoising strength：0.35-0.6

Upscale by：1.5-2

items.name: Shiranui(Onmyoji)
items.description:
使用前必读

重要：一定要填写触发词语：Shiranui

底模为 Anything3.0 ，经过测试，个人感觉在 anything3.0中有比较好的状态。

  • 在 Anything 3.0 的模型下，较好的参数为 0.6 - 0.8 之间

  • 在 counterfeit2.5 的模型下也能获得比较好的效果，但整体颜色会略淡，尝试加高参数，或者使用 vae 改善部分效果

  • 该模型对类 chilloutmix 模型（其他真人模型一样）适配并不是特别好，整体表现为：颜色过淡、形态不够

需要注意的是：因为阿离在 CG 以及立绘中包含太多蝴蝶、樱花的元素，这类元素在 ai 学习的过程中很难去除，所以你会发现用了此 lora 的图会带上很多这类内容。（想要降低这部分可以通过添加反向 Prompt ，或者调低参数）

ReadMe

Important: Always fill in the trigger word: Shiranui

The bottom mold is anything3.0. After testing, I personally feel that it is in good condition in anything3.0.

Under the model of anything 3.0, the better parameters are between 0.6 and 0.8

Better results can also be obtained under the counterfeit2.5 model, but the overall color will be slightly lighter. Try to increase the parameters or use vae to improve some effects

The model is not particularly suitable for the model like chilloutmix (like other human models). The overall performance is that the color is too light and the shape is not enough

It should be noted that because Ali contains too many elements of butterflies and cherry blossoms in CG and vertical painting, it is difficult to remove these elements in the process of AI learning, so you will find that using this Lora will bring a lot of these elements. (To reduce this part, you can add a reverse Prompt or lower the parameter)

items.name: PhotoSomnia
items.description:
Dream with your Eyes Wide Open

Please enjoy PhotoSomnia, a general-purpose model merge blended and adjusted with an objective of emulating film photography, with some success.

Q. Isn't this just another model blend?

A. Short answer - No, this is the best photorealism model you'll find today.

Long answer - Yes, imo the people who are training/fine tuning and are sharing their models/embeddings/etc. are the real heroes of the AI art community! But this is an excellent photorealism blend for a few reasons - it's been the most responsive to prompts than any others I have tried, and seems biased towards producing photorealistic outputs. Also despite the incorporation of many nsfw models, it doesn't seem as biased towards producing NSFW outputs as many other photorealism blends, I consider this a positive.

Q. Isn't this just a rip-off of Analog Diffusion/Dreamlike Photoreal/any other model?

A. Though both of those models and many others have been involved in the blending process, it seems to produce relatively unique outputs thanks to the weird and chaotic blending workflow I've been using. The influence of certain models on Gravy Mix seemed quite clear, but this blend shouldn't be considered a direct derivative of any model other than Stable Diffusion 1.5.

Q. What models did you use?

A. Anything I could find that appears to be trained on actual photos of actual people, plus some artistic ones and top-quality photorealism merges. It's a big list appended to the end of this blurb, and I hate to admit it but I may have missed some, and also may not have used some on the list, but they're in my models folder and are quite likely to have been used.

Q. What ratios are they blended at?

Calculating the ratio of any contributing model would be impossible. My general approach since Gravy Mix has been to grab the latest photo-trained/fine-tuned model I can find and use the either the weighted sum/add difference merge at a low ratio with the Work in Progress model, reduce all the weightings across the board once things start to get a bit overdone, and continue the process with various models to steer things towards my idea of photorealism as best possible until I'm satisfied with the results I'm getting.

It's not as scientific as A+B ratio blends nor as controlled as block merging which I never found the time to experiment with. It's an open-ended exercise but I think the results are aesthetically pleasing enough at this stage for this model to be shared. I presume that AI-assisted blending tools running on more capable systems than my old mid-tier gaming laptop will soon make this sort of approach obsolete, especially with SDXL as a base.

Q. The outputs are blurry/weird/fake looking/suck :(

A. I'm ok with the softness and other quirks of the outputs. I've blended this model for myself and will share it with the community as it is, if they aren't useful for the style you are aiming for feel free to try using it for your own model blends to suit your own styles, or use this model for composition and img2img or controlnet with your preferred model to achieve the results you're after.

Q. What settings/prompts should I use?

A. Check the metadata of the demo pics for some examples.

Q. What licensing applies to this model?

A. It's my gift back to the community that has made so much possible for me. My understanding is that despite using other models to make PhotoSomnia, this is not a direct or provable derivative of any model other than Stable Diffusion 1.5, thus Open RAIL-M should apply. Whether or not the or not the publishers of the models listed below agree with the above licensing terms is between the user and them.

If your are using this model I would greatly appreciate attribution considering how much time and effort I've put into this, but it's not a requirement.

Q. Will there be updates?

A. The final version is final; While this is one of the best photorealism models available I'm no good at hyping it so it's slipped under the radar for most users.

Model Merge List (updated for latest version):

iirc these are trained/finetuned models that have been used at some stage of developing this blend:

Absolute Reality

Analog Diffusion

modelVersions.name: vFinal
modelVersions.description:
Seems like a massive leap ahead from 1.8 in a lot of ways, but hasn't been thoroughly tested. With the upcoming release of SDXL this will be the final update. Photosomnia vFinal Incorporates some of the latest and best trained photorealism models and some other updated blends that have been released since 1.8, now included in the list.

Thanks to all the model makers for making this merge possible and freely available to share with the community!


Recommended settings for photorealism:

CFG - 4-9 for most samplers, 2-4 for UniPC; Karras samplers are recommended.

Clip Skip 1 or 2 or even 4. 1 is most responsive to prompting. Higher Clip Skips are more susceptible to CFG burn.

Faces are still problematic at lower resolutions but easily fixable with hires fix, img2img upscaling, or inpainting.


For best results use negative photorealism embeddings, I've found in practice that it's ok to combine multiple ones, though some are skewed to hide hands rather than fix them or will have other biases.

This model merge should work well with most Loras.

modelVersions.name: v1.8
modelVersions.description:
More balancing after testing out all the photorealism models I have, re-using the ones that perform best for portrait details and responsiveness to prompts. The Model Toolkit Extension for the A1111 webUI played an essential role in improving the resulting merged model. v1.8 does more natural and realistic composition including better quality hands and faces from txt2img; v1.6 responds to style prompting ( e.g. "analog film photo") more effectively for photorealistic aesthetics , making it great for upscaling via img2img or controlnet.

The VAE is embedded bc the model really does need it to work well.

modelVersions.name: v1.6
modelVersions.description:
1.4 was significantly rebalanced until a significant and consistent improvement occurred. 1.5 was coming along nicely and I was going to release it after a bit more testing...

but after merging it with Mega model 1.1 as a simple 50/50 Weighted Sum just to see what happens I'm once again amazed by the power of Stable Diffusion. MM is incredibly flexible for artistic and responsive to prompting. My workflow usually involves manually selecting pics to upscale but with this I'm using the hires fix because it consistently delivers great composition and detail. Hopefully you will find it as useful and enjoyable as I have.

v1.8 does more natural and realistic composition including better quality hands and faces from txt2img; v1.6 responds to style prompting ( e.g. "analog film photo") more effectively for photorealistic aesthetics , making it great for upscaling via img2img or controlnet.

modelVersions.name: V1.4
modelVersions.description:
V1.4 notes:

A successor to Gravy Mix. V1.0-1.3 seemed like a big leap forward from G.M. but aren't worth uploading compared to V1.4

I have only tested this with the Automatic1111 webUI locally.

the .safetensors file has the VAE baked in. The .ckpt file is a conversion of the .safetensors and may have inherited the baked-in VAE as the outputs are virtually identical. The models are not pruned but it's fp16 and barely over 2GB so pruning seems unnecessary. Also the .ckpt seems to work just fine without the config file.

I don't typically use embeddings/hypernetworks/Loras so you'll have to see for yourself how compatible this is with your favorite ones.

CFFB: back to the viewer;

items.name: 千利休sen no rikyu(Fate/GrandOrder)
items.description:
sen no rikyu LoRA

Generation with "AOM3" is not a problem, but the eyes become too cute.

Using "doll774" will make the eyes closer to their original atmosphere, but the body will become somewhat muscular.

In that case, adding "muscular" to the negative prompt will improve it somewhat.

Poses are influenced by the training data, so it is recommended to use a control net rather than controlling them with a prompt.

The compatibility with anime-style model data is somewhat poor.

Trigger Words:rikyu

Auxiliary prompt:japanese clothes,hat

Tips for changing costume:Enter (preferred costume: 1.0~1.5) in the prompt. Enter (japanese clothes, hat: 1.0) in the negative prompt.

Tips for hires:Upscaler"R-ESRGAN 4x Anime6B"(denoise0.3~0.5)

For more details on how to use it, please refer to the information in the sample image.(The image generation of v1.0 uses the “Additional Network”.)

On March 20, 2023, additional details on learning information and sample images were added.

千利休LoRA

"AOM3"での生成は問題ありませんが、目がかわいくなり過ぎます。

こちらの"doll774"を使用していただくと目が元々の雰囲気に近くなりますが、体付きがやや筋肉質になります。その場合はネガティブプロンプトに"muscular"を入れると多少改善されます。

アニメ系のモデルデータとはやや相性が悪いです。

ポーズは学習データに引っ張られるのでプロンプトで制御するよりコントロールネットの使用をお勧めします。

トリガーワード:rikyu

補助プロンプト:japanese clothes,hat

着せ替えのコツ:プロンプトに(お好みの衣装:1.0~1.5)を入力。ネガティブプロンプトに(japanese clothes,hat:1.0)を入力。

hiresのコツ:アップスケーラー"R-ESRGAN 4x Anime6B"(denoise0.3~0.5)

その他使い方の詳細はサンプル画像の情報を見てください。(v1.0の画像生成には"Additional Network"を使用しています。)

modelVersions.name: v1.0
modelVersions.description:
Learning settings

前準備として学習用画像の背景は"katanuki"と"GIMP"を使って消しています。学習用画像の半分以上が同じ背景のスクリーンショットの場合は背景もセットで学習されるのでこのほうが良いようです。学習用画像にバリエーションがある場合は背景は消さなくてよいと思います。

As a preliminary step, the background of the learning images is being removed using “katanuki” and “GIMP”. If more than half of the learning images are screenshots with the same background, it seems better to learn the background as a set. If there is variation in the learning images, I think it is not necessary to remove the background.

image count=31

repeats=10

reg image=透明画像使用Use a transparent image.

batch_size=2

epoch=5(max_train_epochs=10)

clip skip=2

seed=42

optimizer_type=AdamW8bit

shuffle_caption

keep_tokens=1

learning_rate=1e-4

text_encoder_lr=5e-5

network_dim=128

network_alpha=64

prior_loss_weight=1.0

items.name: Fallen Angel
items.description:
The Fallen Angel

Always read "About this version" on the left for additional prompting...

I'm thrilled to present my Stable Diffusion model, which I have meticulously trained on a comprehensive dataset. This approach grants me complete control over the base model, allowing me to tailor it to my specific requirements. Remarkably, my generated artwork has garnered significant attention on platforms such as YouTube, Pixiv, and various other sites. However, it's important to note that this particular checkpoint is primarily intended for my personal use.

It is crucial to highlight that my objective revolves around achieving a more authentic anime-like art style, as opposed to imitating 3D renders, semi 3D, or 2.5D styles.

To optimize training speed and enhance the quality of the results, I invested in a used NVIDIA GeForce RTX3090 24GB graphics card. With this hardware upgrade, I can train models more efficiently and produce stunning output. I sincerely hope that this checkpoint fulfills your requirements, and feel free to merge it with your own projects.

For access to additional high-quality checkpoints, please refer to my Stable Diffusion Checkpoint repository, as they are not shared here. Additionally, don't forget to explore my Pixiv profile, where I regularly share exceptional results.

Links

The Toyota Mark II (Japanese: トヨタ・マークII, Hepburn: Toyota Māku Tsū) is a compact, later mid-size sedan manufactured and marketed in Japan by Toyota between 1968 and 2004. Prior to 1972, the model was marketed as the Toyota Corona Mark II. In some export markets, Toyota marketed the vehicle as the Toyota Cressida between 1976 and 1992 across four generations. Toyota replaced the rear-wheel-drive Cressida in North America with the front-wheel-drive Avalon. Every Mark II and Cressida was manufactured at the Motomachi plant at Toyota, Aichi, Japan from September 1968 to October 1993, and later at Toyota Motor Kyushu's Miyata plant from December 1992 to October 2000, with some models also assembled in Jakarta, Indonesia as the Cressida.
